## Issue
hasFetchedRef prevents refetch when dependencies change, potentially leaving stale data if organization_id changes.

## Severity
P2 IMPORTANT - Could show wrong data in multi-org scenarios

## Location
medsimples/frontend/src/components/cognitest/CogniTestNewSession.tsx:91-137

## Why This Matters
If user's organization_id changes (multi-org scenario), the effect dependency triggers but hasFetchedRef=true prevents refetch, showing stale data from previous org.

## Solution
Use cancellation flag instead of ref:
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  if (moduleLoading) return;
  if (!isEnabled) {
    setLoading(false);
    return;
  }

  let cancelled = false;

  const fetchData = async () => {
    if (cancelled) return;

    try {
      setLoading(true);
      // ... fetch logic
    } finally {
      if (!cancelled) {
        setLoading(false);
      }
    }
  };

  fetchData();

  return () => {
    cancelled = true;
  };
}, [isEnabled, moduleLoading, searchParams, user?.organization_id]);
```

## Validation Criteria
- [ ] Remove hasFetchedRef
- [ ] Add cancellation flag
- [ ] Data refetches when organization_id changes
- [ ] No double-fetch in React Strict Mode dev

## Testing Steps
1. Implement cancellation pattern
2. Test normal load
3. Test rapid navigation (verify cleanup)
4. If multi-org: test org switching

## Issue
Promise.all causes entire data load to fail if any single API call fails, making form unusable.

## Severity
P2 IMPORTANT - Poor UX when partial data would be sufficient

## Location
medsimples/frontend/src/components/cognitest/CogniTestNewSession.tsx:104-110

## Why This Matters
If credits API fails but patients/tests load successfully, user can't create session even though they have all required data. Generic error message doesn't indicate which API failed.

## Solution
Use Promise.allSettled for graceful degradation:
```typescript
const results = await Promise.allSettled([
  cachedAxiosGet('/api/patients'),
  cognitestApi.listTestDefinitions(),
  cognitestApi.listTestBatteries(),
  cognitestApi.getOrganizationCredits(organizationId),
]);

const [patientsResult, testsResult, batteriesResult, creditsResult] = results;

if (patientsResult.status === 'fulfilled') {
  setPatients(patientsResult.value.data);
} else {
  console.error('Failed to load patients:', patientsResult.reason);
  setError('Erro ao carregar pacientes');
  return; // Block if critical
}

if (creditsResult.status === 'fulfilled') {
  setCredits(creditsResult.value);
} else {
  console.error('Failed to load credits:', creditsResult.reason);
  // Don't block - credits are optional
}
```

## Validation Criteria
- [ ] Form usable if non-critical APIs fail
- [ ] Specific error messages for each failure
- [ ] Credits failure doesn't block form
- [ ] Patient/test failures properly block form

## Testing Steps
1. Mock API to fail credits endpoint
2. Verify form still works without credits banner
3. Mock API to fail patients endpoint
4. Verify form shows specific error and is blocked

## Issue
Clipboard copy timeout continues firing after user resets form state by clicking 'Criar Outra Sessão'.

## Severity
P1 CRITICAL - Race condition causes React warnings and potential state corruption

## Location
medsimples/frontend/src/components/cognitest/CogniTestNewSession.tsx:177-187

## Why This Matters
When user copies link and clicks 'Criar Outra Sessão' within 2 seconds, the setTimeout callback fires on unmounted/reset component state. This causes React warnings about setting state on unmounted components and could interfere with future clipboard operations.

## Solution
Use useRef to track timeout ID and clear it in cleanup:
```typescript
const timeoutIdRef = useRef<number | null>(null);

const handleCopyLink = async () => {
  if (createdSession?.session_url) {
    try {
      await navigator.clipboard.writeText(createdSession.session_url);
      setCopied(true);

      if (timeoutIdRef.current \!== null) {
        clearTimeout(timeoutIdRef.current);
      }

      timeoutIdRef.current = window.setTimeout(() => {
        setCopied(false);
        timeoutIdRef.current = null;
      }, 2000);
    } catch (err) {
      console.error('Failed to copy:', err);
    }
  }
};

// Clear in reset handler
onClick={() => {
  if (timeoutIdRef.current \!== null) {
    clearTimeout(timeoutIdRef.current);
  }
  setCopied(false);
  setCreatedSession(null);
  setSelectedPatient(null);
  setSelectedBattery('');
}}
```

## Validation Criteria
- [ ] Timeout is cleared when user clicks 'Criar Outra Sessão'
- [ ] No React warnings in console about setState on unmounted component
- [ ] Copied state properly resets

## Testing Steps
1. Create a session successfully
2. Click copy link button
3. Within 2 seconds, click 'Criar Outra Sessão'
4. Check console for warnings
5. Verify copied state resets immediately

## Issue
formatDuration utility is duplicated in CogniTestNewSession.tsx and CogniTestResults.tsx (22 total lines).

## Severity
P1 CRITICAL - Code duplication violates DRY principle, creates maintenance burden

## Location
- medsimples/frontend/src/components/cognitest/CogniTestNewSession.tsx:50-61
- medsimples/frontend/src/components/cognitest/CogniTestResults.tsx:138-148

## Why This Matters
Changes must be synchronized across files. Risk of divergence if updated in one place but not the other.

## Solution
Extract to shared utility at medsimples/frontend/src/utils/formatters.ts:
```typescript
// utils/formatters.ts
export const formatDuration = (seconds: number | null): string => {
  if (\!seconds) return '-';
  const minutes = Math.floor(seconds / 60);
  const remainingSeconds = Math.round(seconds % 60);
  if (minutes > 0) {
    return `${minutes}m ${remainingSeconds}s`;
  }
  return `${remainingSeconds}s`;
};

// Both components import:
import { formatDuration } from '../../utils/formatters';
```

